"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165903","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-28","<p>Whilst NESTA's internal review highlights that Lord Wei, among others, made a request suggesting that they consider various initiatives, no formal instruction from Government was made. NESTA’s internal review is also clear that this was not an instruction from the Government. Lord Wei was not a Government Minister.</p><p>We constantly keep procedures and policies under review. In this instance, NESTA’s internal review did not highlight anything of relevance in this regard.</p><p>Lord Wei did not request that that NESTA fund any organisations and, therefore, there is no such correspondence.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165903/answer",,,,,"215996 ; 215997 ; 215999","2014-11-28T14:40:22.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165903/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165903/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-25","NESTA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the internal review by Geoff Mulgan published on 21 August 2014 on NESTA support for the Big Society Network, who authorised the approach by Lord Wei to NESTA on the funding of the Your Local Budget project; and which other bodies Lord Wei approached on the funding of that project.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","215998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165904","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-28","<p>Whilst NESTA's internal review highlights that Lord Wei, among others, made a request suggesting that they consider various initiatives, no formal instruction from Government was made. NESTA’s internal review is also clear that this was not an instruction from the Government. Lord Wei was not a Government Minister.</p><p>We constantly keep procedures and policies under review. In this instance, NESTA’s internal review did not highlight anything of relevance in this regard.</p><p>Lord Wei did not request that that NESTA fund any organisations and, therefore, there is no such correspondence.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165904/answer",,,,,"215996 ; 215997 ; 215998","2014-11-28T14:40:22.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165904/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165904/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-25","NESTA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies and procedures of the internal review by Geoff Mulgan published on 21 August 2014 on NESTA support for the Big Society Network; and what changes he plans to make to his Department's procedures and processes as a result.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","215999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165905","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-28","<p>Earlier this year, the Chancellor set out plans to make Britain the global centre of financial innovation, benefitting consumers and businesses, including a major programme of work looking at the benefits and risks of digital currencies, and to look into whether they could or should be regulated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On 3 November, the Treasury published a Call for Information on digital currencies. This Call for Information asks whether there are currently barriers to digital currency businesses setting up in the UK, and the Government will consider access to UK bank accounts as part of this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In October, the Financial Conduct Authority launched its Innovation Hub to provide support to innovative businesses. It has identified helping innovators access bank accounts as a key priority.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165905/answer",,,,,"215985","2014-11-28T14:11:53.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165905/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165905/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Bitcoin","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the ability of companies dealing with bitcoin to open a bank account.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","215986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165906","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-10","<p>The proportion of the cost of income tax relief on pension contributions for the given income ranges, and years, is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="6"><p><strong>% of the cost of income tax relief on contributions</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Income bands</strong></p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Up to £19,999</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Between £20,000 and £44,999</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td><td><p>32%</p></td><td><p>35%</p></td><td><p>37%</p></td><td><p>37%</p></td><td><p>36%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Between £45,000 and £74,999</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td><td><p>28%</p></td><td><p>32%</p></td><td><p>33%</p></td><td><p>34%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Between £75,000 and £99,999</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Between £100,000 and £149,999</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>9%</p></td><td><p>9%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£150,000 or more</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Estimates are based on Surveys of Personal Incomes with projections for 2012-13 onwards. Historical estimates have been updated to take into account the latest outturn data and updated projections. Projected years are subject to uncertainty.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The effect of the reductions in the Annual Allowance in 2011‑12 and Lifetime Allowance from 2012-13, as well as further reductions in both allowances in 2014-15 are reflected in the table. These restrictions mostly affect individuals with incomes over £150,000 hence the drop in share of tax relief for these individuals in latter years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Increases in the Personal Allowance (from £6,475 in 2009-10 to £10,000 in 2014-15) cause a decline in the share of income tax relief going to those in the “Up to £19,999” income band. The higher personal allowance reduces the amount of income subject to tax for these individuals, hence also reduces their share of tax relief.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165906/answer",,,,,"211726","2014-12-10T11:15:09.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165906/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165906/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Pensions: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 20 February 2012 to Question 95617, what estimate he has made of the proportion of income tax relief on contributions accruing to individuals with an annual income of (a) up to £19,999, (b) between £20,000 and £44,999, (c) between £45,000 and £74,999, (d) between £75,000 and £99,999, (e) between £100,000 and £149,999 and (f) over £150,000 in (i) 2010-11, (ii) 2011-12, (iii) 2012-13, (iv) 2013-14 and (v) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","215992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165907","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-02","<p>HMT installed water saving taps in the toilets in 2012 and installed additional water meters in August 2014. The additional water meters will measure water usage in the tea points, showers and toilets to enable us more accurately target water saving measures. This will lead to a reduction in bills.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165907/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T16:47:10.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165907/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165907/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165908","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-28","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of organisations as part of the usual policy making process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It might be useful to know that the Treasury publishes a list of ministerial meetings with external organisations. This is available online at: <a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is currently undertaking a review of the effectiveness of the Current Account Switch Service. Alongside this review the FCA is also gathering evidence on other options to improve switching, including account number portability. The FCA expects to conclude its review in the first quarter of 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165908/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T14:13:30.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165908/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165908/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Bank Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the banking industry on full account number portability.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","215855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165909","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-03","<p>Estimates of the number of individuals by Scottish parliamentary constituency whose highest marginal rate of income tax was the basic rate and the higher or additional rates for the tax years 2007-08, 2009-10, 2010-11 and 2011-12 are provided in the table attached.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165909/answer","tables.docx","tables.docx","higher/additional rate taxpayers table","higher/additional rate taxpayers table",,"2014-12-03T13:29:56.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165909/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165909/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people paid the (a) top rate, (b) higher rate and (c) basic rate of income tax in each Scottish parliamentary constituency in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","215843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165910","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-28","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) publishes quarterly information about our telephony performance, which is available on GOV.UK: <br><br>www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-plan-indicators</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165910/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T14:35:43.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165910/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165910/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average length of time taken to answer calls to tax credit helplines was in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","215872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165911","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-01","<p>Under the Financial Conduct Authority’s (FCA) consumer protection remit, it has already responsibility for ensuring that regulated firms treat their customers fairly and communicate in a way that is clear, fair, and not misleading. The FCA also has powers to take action against firms which engage in unauthorised business.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165911/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T15:11:45.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165911/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165911/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will discuss with the Financial Conduct Authority ways of ensuring that people with personal pensions becoming payable from April 2015 are aware of the potential drawbacks as well as advantages of transferring their pensions.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","215874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165912","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-01","<p>Since 2000, HMRC’s tobacco fraud strategy has reduced the illicit market for cigarettes from 22% in 2000/01 to 10% in 2013/14, and the illicit market for hand-rolling tobacco from 61% to 39% in the same period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The current strategy to tackle tobacco smuggling was launched in 2011 and adopts a holistic approach to tackling the problem overseas, at the border and within the UK. This includes continual monitoring of intelligence to assess and respond to changes in criminal behaviours, partnership working with other enforcement agencies, such as Trading Standards, and use of a wide range of interventions and sanctions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The strategy can be accessed on the HMRC website: <a href="http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageImport_ShowContent&amp;id=HMCE_PROD1_031246&amp;propertyType=document" target="_blank">http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageImport_ShowContent&amp;id=HMCE_PROD1_031246&amp;propertyType=document</a></p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165912/answer",,,,,"215878","2014-12-01T15:13:06.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165912/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165912/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to recover revenue lost to the illicit trade in tobacco.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","215877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165913","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-28","<p>The cost to print and post annual tax summaries was published in response to Parliamentary question number 213257 on 11 November.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Tax summaries are being sent to around 24 million taxpayers. Individuals will not receive a tax summary if they have paid no income tax in the past year, or where HMRC is awaiting updated PAYE information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC undertook in-depth customer research to test with taxpayers whether they found the information on tax summaries clear and comprehensive.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165913/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T14:33:34.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165913/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165913/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to his Department of printing and distributing personal tax summaries; on what criteria it was determined who would receive such summaries; what representations he has received on the wording used in those documents; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","215891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165914","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-01","<p>Since 2000, HMRC’s tobacco fraud strategy has reduced the illicit market for cigarettes from 22% in 2000/01 to 10% in 2013/14, and the illicit market for hand-rolling tobacco from 61% to 39% in the same period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The current strategy to tackle tobacco smuggling was launched in 2011 and adopts a holistic approach to tackling the problem overseas, at the border and within the UK. This includes continual monitoring of intelligence to assess and respond to changes in criminal behaviours, partnership working with other enforcement agencies, such as Trading Standards, and use of a wide range of interventions and sanctions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The strategy can be accessed on the HMRC website: <a href="http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageImport_ShowContent&amp;id=HMCE_PROD1_031246&amp;propertyType=document" target="_blank">http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageImport_ShowContent&amp;id=HMCE_PROD1_031246&amp;propertyType=document</a></p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165914/answer",,,,,"215877","2014-12-01T15:13:06.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165914/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165914/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to tackle the illicit trade in tobacco.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","215878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165915","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-02","<p>HMRC has carried out a “futures analysis” to identify the potential impact the introduction of Standardised Packaging could have on the illicit trade in tobacco. This assessment has been shared with the Department of Health to inform the development of Government policy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The assessment is currently being reviewed taking into consideration additional information provided during the Government consultation.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165915/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T16:45:37.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165915/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165915/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of standardised packaging of tobacco products on the illicit trade in tobacco.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","215879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165916","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-01","<p>The most recent estimates of the total revenue losses associated with the tobacco illicit market were published on 16 October in the report ‘Tobacco tax gap estimates 2013-14’.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This can be accessed on the HMRC website:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/364011/141016_Tobacco_Tax_Gap_2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/364011/141016_Tobacco_Tax_Gap_2014.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to disaggregate losses to organised crime from total losses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165916/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T15:05:26.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165916/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165916/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate has he made of the cost to the public purse of organised crime associated with the trade in illicit tobacco.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","215880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165917","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-02","<p>The HMRC/Border Force strategy to tackle tobacco smuggling is in place and would adapt to any changes in risks as it has done over many years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC and other enforcement agencies will adjust their response as necessary, to reflect any new risks.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165917/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T17:28:12.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165917/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165917/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-25","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the trade in illicit tobacco of the forthcoming ban on menthol cigarettes and 10-packs of cigarettes.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","215881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165918","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-12-02","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government has made significant reductions to both its water usage and associated bills.</p><p> </p><p>Total water use has been reduced by 50% since 2009-10, and the number of its offices falling within good and best practice office water benchmarks has been increased from 28% to 73% during the same period.</p><p> </p><p>These improvements have primarily been achieved by installing efficiency devices such as tap aerators, flow control valves, through leak reduction work, and by encouraging staff and facilities managers to adopt more water efficient behaviours.</p><p> </p><p>In taking this action, the Department has reduced its annual water bill by £13,000 since 2009-10, and continues to work towards identifying even greater efficiencies.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165918/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T17:11:26.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165918/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165918/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165919","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-01-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement of 18 December, <em>Official Report</em>, Columns 110-118WS, which outlines my Department’s spending profile on integration.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of integration projects are led by charities, businesses and faith groups, some in partnership with local authorities. The following local authorities have received funding directly from my Department for projects listed in that Written Ministerial Statement:<br><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Project </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Local authority</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Funding</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Arts and Communities</p><p>Arts and Communities</p><p>Arts and Communities</p></td><td><p>Birmingham</p><p>Bradford</p><p>Burnley</p></td><td><p>£80,000</p><p>£80,000</p><p>£80,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>English Language</p><p>English Language</p><p>English Language</p></td><td><p>City of London</p><p>Manchester</p><p>Slough</p></td><td><p>£819,000</p><p>£1,076,593</p><p>£48,674</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gurkha Fund</p></td><td><p>Rushmoor</p></td><td><p>£1,500,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Special Interest Group on the English Defence League</p></td><td><p>Blackburn with Darwen</p></td><td><p><br><br>£200,000</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>World War One – Woking Peace Garden</p></td><td><p>Woking</p></td><td><p>£50,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165919/answer",,,,,,"2015-01-15T17:23:34.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165919/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165919/answer","Bristol West","Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165919/answer/previousversion/30695","Biography information for Stephen Williams","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-11-25","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding his Department (a) spends directly on and (b) allocates to local authorities for integration work.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","215987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165921","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>DCMS is a tenant of HMRC at 100 Parliament Street and responsibility for water usage rests with them.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165921/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T14:08:50.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165921/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165921/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165922","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>The <em>Final Report on the Independent Review of the proposed programme of works in the restoration of the Flying Scotsman Locomotive 4427</em> by First Class Partnerships Rail Consultants dated 27 February 2013 is published on the website of the National Railway Museum:<a href="http://www.nrm.org.uk/~/media/Files/NRM/PDF/NRM%20Flying%20Scotsman%20Final%20Report.pdf?keywords=first+class+partnerships" target="_blank">http://www.nrm.org.uk/~/media/Files/NRM/PDF/NRM%20Flying%20Scotsman%20Final%20Report.pdf?keywords=first+class+partnerships</a>.</p><p>The Report contained certain redactions relating to information which is regarded as being commercially sensitive in accordance with section 43 of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 (‘FOIA’). Further redactions within the Report were made to protect the personal data of individuals in accordance with section 40 of FOIA and the Museum’s obligations under the Data Protection Act 1998.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165922/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T11:14:58.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165922/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165922/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Flying Scotsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will place in the Library a copy of the full report by First Class Partnerships on restoration of the Flying Scotsman conducted for the Science Museum Group and dated 27 February 2014.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","215948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165923","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p> </p><p>There are no current plans for the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport to meet with the chairman and chief executive of Sianel 4 Cymru before 31 March 2015. However, he previously met the Chairman and the Chief Executive, as well as other S4C representatives, during a visit to S4C’s Headquarters in Llanishen, Cardiff on 17th July this year. The previous Secretary of State, Maria Miller, also met with both Huw Jones and Ian Jones on 13<sup>th</sup> November 2013. In these meetings future funding was discussed.</p><p> </p><p>All such meetings are detailed in the Department’s regularly published transparency returns: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=dcms+ministerial+meetings&amp;publication_filter_option=transparency-data&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-culture-media-sport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=dcms+ministerial+meetings&amp;publication_filter_option=transparency-data&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-culture-media-sport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results</a></p><p> </p><p>Officials from DCMS are in regular contact with S4C equivalents on a range of issues. S4C, as with all publicly funded bodies, has its Exchequer funding set out to the end of the current SR period. This means that in 2015/16 S4C will continue to receive £6.787m of funding from DCMS. In addition to this, the current operating agreement between the BBC and S4C sets out further licence fee funding for 2016-17 (£74.5m).</p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165923/answer",,,,,"215924 ; 215925","2014-12-02T16:58:23.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165923/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165923/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","S4C","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he plans to meet the (a) chairman and (b) chief executive of Sianel 4 Cymru before 31 March 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","215923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165924","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>Superfast broadband has already been made available to over 110,000 premises in Scotland and we are working closely with the Scottish Government and suppliers to maintain the pace of delivery which has increased to an average across the whole of the UK to 40,000 premises a week.</p><p>The roll-out in Scotland is on schedule to deliver superfast broadband to 70% coverage to some of the most remote and challenging locations in the Highlands &amp; Islands and 95% to the Rest of Scotland by the end of 2017.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165924/answer",,,,,"215844","2014-12-02T11:11:14.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165924/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165924/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband: Kilmarnock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will discuss with ministers of the Scottish government how faster progress can be made on making broadband available to rural communities in Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","215946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165925","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>The UK has a highly competitive broadband market. Superfast broadband is currently available to 78% of UK premises, up from 45% in 2010. BT’s wholesale access products are open to all Internet Service Providers, meaning that consumers have a range of retail Internet Service providers to buy broadband services from. In addition to BT, KCom and Virgin Media, a growing number of both fixed and wireless providers are making investments in competing broadband infrastructure. In September 2012 the Government announced a package of measures to reduce the barriers to deployment of superfast broadband, reducing red tape and bureaucracy to enable communications providers to deploy competing networks.</p><p>In August 2014 the Government consulted on the objectives for a long term digital communications infrastructure strategy to ensure the UK maintains its competitive position. We expect the strategy to be published early in 2015.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165925/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T11:16:24.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165925/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165925/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to promote competition in the provision of superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","215927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165926","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>According to Ofcom’s Communications Market Report 2014, by the end of Q1 2014 over a quarter (26.7%) of broadband connections were superfast. A breakdown between cable and non-cable premises was not given. The same publication reported that as of June 2014 superfast broadband was available to 78% of premises.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165926/answer",,,,,"215926","2014-12-02T10:21:44.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165926/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165926/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the UK population has taken-up super-fast broadband, excluding cable.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","215912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165927","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>According to Ofcom’s Communications Market Report 2014, by the end of Q1 2014 over a quarter (26.7%) of broadband connections were superfast. A breakdown between cable and non-cable premises was not given. The same publication reported that as of June 2014 superfast broadband was available to 78% of premises.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165927/answer",,,,,"215912","2014-12-02T10:21:44.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165927/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165927/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the UK population has access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","215926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165928","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p> </p><p>There are no current plans for the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport to meet with the chairman and chief executive of Sianel 4 Cymru before 31 March 2015. However, he previously met the Chairman and the Chief Executive, as well as other S4C representatives, during a visit to S4C’s Headquarters in Llanishen, Cardiff on 17th July this year. The previous Secretary of State, Maria Miller, also met with both Huw Jones and Ian Jones on 13<sup>th</sup> November 2013. In these meetings future funding was discussed.</p><p> </p><p>All such meetings are detailed in the Department’s regularly published transparency returns: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=dcms+ministerial+meetings&amp;publication_filter_option=transparency-data&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-culture-media-sport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=dcms+ministerial+meetings&amp;publication_filter_option=transparency-data&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-culture-media-sport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results</a></p><p> </p><p>Officials from DCMS are in regular contact with S4C equivalents on a range of issues. S4C, as with all publicly funded bodies, has its Exchequer funding set out to the end of the current SR period. This means that in 2015/16 S4C will continue to receive £6.787m of funding from DCMS. In addition to this, the current operating agreement between the BBC and S4C sets out further licence fee funding for 2016-17 (£74.5m).</p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165928/answer",,,,,"215923 ; 215924","2014-12-02T16:58:23.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165928/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165928/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","S4C","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with Sianel 4 Cymru on future funding for that organisation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","215925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165929","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p> </p><p>There are no current plans for the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport to meet with the chairman and chief executive of Sianel 4 Cymru before 31 March 2015. However, he previously met the Chairman and the Chief Executive, as well as other S4C representatives, during a visit to S4C’s Headquarters in Llanishen, Cardiff on 17th July this year. The previous Secretary of State, Maria Miller, also met with both Huw Jones and Ian Jones on 13<sup>th</sup> November 2013. In these meetings future funding was discussed.</p><p> </p><p>All such meetings are detailed in the Department’s regularly published transparency returns: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=dcms+ministerial+meetings&amp;publication_filter_option=transparency-data&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-culture-media-sport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=dcms+ministerial+meetings&amp;publication_filter_option=transparency-data&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-culture-media-sport&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results</a></p><p> </p><p>Officials from DCMS are in regular contact with S4C equivalents on a range of issues. S4C, as with all publicly funded bodies, has its Exchequer funding set out to the end of the current SR period. This means that in 2015/16 S4C will continue to receive £6.787m of funding from DCMS. In addition to this, the current operating agreement between the BBC and S4C sets out further licence fee funding for 2016-17 (£74.5m).</p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165929/answer",,,,,"215923 ; 215925","2014-12-02T16:58:23.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165929/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165929/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","S4C","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he or his predecessor last met the (a) Chairman and (b) Chief Executive of Sianel 4 Cymru.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","215924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165930","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>Ofcom is responsible for monitoring broadband markets and publishes Superfast broadband coverage and take-up data by local authority area on their UK Fixed Broadband Map. The 2013 edition is available at: <a href="http://maps.ofcom.org.uk/broadband/" target="_blank">http://maps.ofcom.org.uk/broadband/</a> Ofcom’s 2014 Infrastructure Report is expected to be published in early December. However, the data is not normally available by population as the usual measurement is by premises and the analysis by project is not currently available.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165930/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T10:25:14.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165930/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165930/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the UK population has taken-up super-fast broadband that has been funded or partially funded by BDUK or a local authority.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","215911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165932","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-28","<p>Further to the answer I gave the hon. Member for East Londonderry on 12 May, Official Report, col 305W, there are no current plans to make such proposals<em>. </em>The Government has said that the right time to consider all aspects of the BBC is the Charter Review; this will not be starting in advance of the Election in 2015.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165932/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T10:31:30.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165932/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165932/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","BBC","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make it his policy to propose to the BBC, as part of the forthcoming negotiations on renewal of its Royal Charter, that under a renewed Charter the BBC should be required to demonstrate more transparency about fees, expenses and salaries paid to all staff or employees of the Corporation who earn more than £100,000 per annum.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","215893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165933","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>I have invited the major mobile network operators to a round table meeting in January to confirm details of the liability caps they will offer for unauthorised use of lost or stolen ‘phones.</p><p>We are tackling the problem of high bills when ‘phones are lost or stolen through the Telecommunications Consumer Action Plan.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165933/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T10:27:51.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165933/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165933/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Mobile Phones: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will have discussions with mobile telephone companies on measures to prevent victims of mobile telephone theft having to pay excessive bills on their stolen telephones.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","215886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165934","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-28","<p>Ofcom is responsible for monitoring broadband markets and publishes Superfast broadband coverage and take-up data by local authority area on their UK Fixed Broadband Map. The 2013 edition is available at: <a href="http://maps.ofcom.org.uk/broadband/" target="_blank">http://maps.ofcom.org.uk/broadband/</a> Ofcom’s 2014 Infrastructure Report is expected to be published in early December.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165934/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T10:30:48.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165934/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165934/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if his Department will commission, in conjunction with the devolved administrations, research into the penetration of high-speed broadband services in rural areas.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","215896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165935","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>Mobile and broadband data is available for East Ayrshire local authority, but not at a constituency level.</p><p>According to the most recent figures from Ofcom in 2013 in East Ayrshire, 89.0% of premises could get a 2G signal from three mobile operators and 99.9% from at least one of them, and 8.2% of premises could get a 3G signal from all four mobile operators and 74.3% from at least one of them - <a href="http://d2a9983j4okwzn.cloudfront.net/downloads/ofcom-uk-mobile-coverage-data-2013.csv" target="_blank">http://d2a9983j4okwzn.cloudfront.net/downloads/ofcom-uk-mobile-coverage-data-2013.csv</a></p><p>Ofcom’s Communications Market Report 2014 states that current generation broadband is available to close to 100% of UK premises and Next Generation Access (NGA) broadband is available to 78% of premises in the UK and to 64% of premises in Scotland. Ofcom reported that NGA broadband availability in East Ayrshire in spring 2013 was about 37.2% - <a href="http://d2a9983j4okwzn.cloudfront.net/downloads/ofcom-uk-broadband-speed-data-2013.csv" target="_blank">http://d2a9983j4okwzn.cloudfront.net/downloads/ofcom-uk-broadband-speed-data-2013.csv</a></p><p>Ofcom will be publishing its annual UK Infrastructure Report shortly which will include more recent data on levels of mobile and broadband coverage.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165935/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T10:49:01.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165935/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165935/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband: Kilmarnock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of households in Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency are covered by (a) mobile telephone signal and (b) broadband.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","215863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165936","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>Superfast broadband has already been made available to over 110,000 premises in Scotland and we are working closely with the Scottish Government and suppliers to maintain the pace of delivery which has increased to an average across the whole of the UK to 40,000 premises a week.</p><p>The roll-out in Scotland is on schedule to deliver superfast broadband to 70% coverage to some of the most remote and challenging locations in the Highlands &amp; Islands and 95% to the Rest of Scotland by the end of 2017.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165936/answer",,,,,"215946","2014-12-02T11:11:14.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165936/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165936/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Broadband: Kilmarnock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will discuss with the Scottish Government steps to increase progress on the roll out of superfast broadband in Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","215844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165937","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-12-02","<p>Waterloo 200 Ltd are the umbrella organisation supported by the Government to oversee the commemoration of the 200th anniversary of the Battle of Waterloo. There are a number of events taking place in Scotland. These so far include Waterloo related Regimental exhibitions at the National Army Museum in Edinburgh and at the Gordon Highlanders Museum in Aberdeen, a Black Watch Regimental Muster in Aberfeldy, a commemorative event at the Waterloo Monumnet at Penielhuegh and a Royal Scots Dragoon Guards march down the Royal Mile in Edinburgh followed by a service of Commemoration in Canongate.</p><p>In addition to this, the Heritage Lottery fund has awarded a grant to a project in Kilmarnock focusing on the Battle of Waterloo and the life of local Kilmarnock man, Charles Ewart and his capture of Napoleon's standard.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165937/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T11:13:11.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165937/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165937/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","Battle of Waterloo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on plans to hold events in Scotland to commemorate the Battle of Waterloo.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","215842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165938","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-28","<p>The events DCMS hosted on 4th August set a fitting tone and struck a chord with the public. This month my RT. Hon. Friend, the Prime Minister, announced a memorable and dignified programme of events to commemorate the Gallipoli campaign. Alongside the Department for Communities and Local Government and other partners we are also offering a variety of programmes that are allowing local communities to mark the centenary in their own way, including the restoration of War memorials, school battlefield visits and the honouring of local VC recipients.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165938/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T10:32:08.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165938/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165938/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-25","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he has made in ensuring that the First World War is appropriately commemorated.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","215838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165939","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-01","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 20 October 2014 (Official Report, column 671) to the member for Gloucester (Mr Graham).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165939/answer","20141021 - Hansard Extract Type 26 Frigates.doc","20141021 - Hansard Extract Type 26 Frigates.doc","Hansard extract on Type 26 Frigates","Hansard extract on Type 26 Frigates",,"2014-12-01T16:46:00.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165939/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165939/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Type 26 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent progress he has made on the awarding of contracts for the Type 26 Global Combat Ship.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165940","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-02","<p>As part of the Army 2020 programme, 7,280 Service personnel were made redundant in tranches 1 to 3 of the Armed Forces Redundancy Programme and around 1,000 personnel were selected in the fourth and final tranche, the majority of whom will have left the Army by June 2015. All personnel selected receive at least six months notice, twelve if they did not apply for redundancy. On leaving the Armed Forces, personnel cease to be entitled to occupy Service Family Accommodation (SFA). While the Ministry of Defence will always be as flexible as possible in order to allow families the maximum time to secure alternative accommodation, on occasions it becomes necessary to proceed to eviction action in order that properties can be made available to entitled Service families. To date, a total of three Army personnel made redundant under the Armed Forces Redundancy Programme have been evicted from SFA.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165940/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T16:19:48.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165940/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165940/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many soldiers made redundant under the Army 2020 programme have been evicted from family quarters.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165941","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Readiness Action Plan, as agreed by Heads of State and UK Government at the Wales Summit, is a response to the changed security environment in Eastern Europe arising from Russia's actions in and around Ukraine. Its implementation will significantly enhance NATO's readiness and responsiveness. Work is progressing rapidly on enhancing the NATO Response Force's capabilities, including development of the Very High Readiness Joint Task Force.</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165941/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:09:03.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165941/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165941/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Ukraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the progress made by NATO in training and developing Rapid Reaction Forces in response to the situation in Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165942","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-02","<p>The Ministry of Defence aims to complete all housing adaptations for wounded service personnel in the shortest timescale possible.</p><p>No targets are set for the completion of this work as every requirement is unique depending on the needs of the occupants.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165942/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T16:09:41.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165942/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165942/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what targets his Department sets for the time taken to make housing adaptations for wounded service personnel.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165943","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-02","<p>The missile tubes for the Successor Programme are being procured as part of the collaborative Common Missile Compartment (CMC) project with the US. General Dynamics Electric Boat has been awarded an $83.8 million contract modification by the US Department of Defense to continue development of the CMC.</p><p> </p><p>The contract provides funding for 17 missile tubes; four for the US submarine programme, one for a US shore test facility and 12 missile tubes for the Successor Programme. The 12 UK missile tubes’ share of this contract is estimated at $59 million. Costs beyond the first 17 tubes have yet to be agreed, and it would prejudice commercial interests to estimate costs at this stage. The Ministry of Defence is not planning to commit to further missile tubes prior to Main Gate in 2016.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165943/answer",,,,,"215790","2014-12-02T17:51:55.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165943/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165943/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Trident Missiles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what contracts have been placed for launch tubes for sea-launched Trident nuclear missiles with General Dynamics Electric Boat Company in the US.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","215809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165944","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-28","<p>The total area of land owned by the Ministry of Defence in the UK is 228,000 hectares, of which 3,500 hectares is currently surplus to Defence requirements.</p><p>Details of Ministry of Defence land holdings with asset valuation over £1 million can be found in Chapter Seven of the National Asset Register, last published by HM Treasury in 2007:</p><p>http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm70/7022/7022.pdf</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165944/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:57:27.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165944/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165944/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what (a) land and (b) premises owned by his Department are not in operational use; and what the estimated value of those assets is.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165945","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-28","<p>A list showing the land and buildings outside the UK owned by the Department is attached. Details of Ministry of Defence land holdings with asset valuation over £1 million can be found in Chapter Seven of the National Asset Register, last published by HM Treasury in 2007: http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm70/7022/7022.pdf</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165945/answer","Copy of AP07 1415-NCAR Extract for Overseas Estate Owned(1).xls","Copy of AP07 1415-NCAR Extract for Overseas Estate Owned(1).xls","215950 - MOD Owned Land and Buildings Overseas","215950 - MOD Owned Land and Buildings Overseas",,"2014-11-28T13:56:06.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165945/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165945/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what (a) land and (b) buildings outside the UK are owned by his Department; and what the estimated value of those assets is.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165946","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-03","<p>Due to the requirement to protect competitive tension, all negotiations with commercial bidders are confidential. The intention to continue to manage the movement of munitions at Marchwood Port remains unchanged.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165946/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-03T16:44:10.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165946/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165946/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Marchwood Military Port","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the specifications for the maximum (a) amount of land to be used and (b) quantity of munitions permitted to be stored in future at the Sea Mounting Centre at Marchwood, have been reduced during the course of negotiations with commercial bidders for the lease of land on the Ministry of Defence site; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","215951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165947","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-28","<p>The total running costs, including gas, for Ministry of Defence (MOD) Main Building are not held as it is managed under a PFI contract which covers both the MOD Main Building and the Old War Office Building. The cost of the PFI contract cannot be released as to do so could prejudice commercial interests.</p><p> </p><p>Additional costs of MOD Main Building for 2013-14 are set out below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Item </strong></td><td><strong>Cost for 2013 - 14</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Rates</td><td>£8.3 million</td></tr><tr><td>Electricity</td><td>£2.7 million</td></tr><tr><td>Water</td><td>£0.127 million</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Details of MOD land holdings with asset valuation over £1 million can be found in Chapter seven of the National Asset Register, last published by HM Treasury in 2007: http://www.official-documents.gov.uk/document/cm70/7022/7022.pdf</p><p> </p><p>The National Asset Register is on a historic replacement cost basis, not market value. We do not routinely assess the current market value of all our estate because the estimated receipts will depend on market conditions and other factors.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165947/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:57:06.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165947/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165947/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the running cost was of MOD Main Building in 2013-14; and what the estimated value of that building is.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165948","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-02","<p>We have defined Ministry of Defence airfields as those capable of supporting fixed wing aircraft. The list of airfields is attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165948/answer","215979 - MOD Airfields.doc","215979 - MOD Airfields.doc","215979 Ministry of Defence Airfields","215979 Ministry of Defence Airfields",,"2014-12-02T17:21:38.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165948/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165948/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what airfields are owned by his Department; and how many flights took off from each such airfield in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15 to date.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165949","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-12-02","<p>In the UK the majority of water consumed on Ministry of Defence (MOD) sites is supplied by three Aquatrine Public Private Partnership contracts. The water supplied under these contractual arrangements equates to 95% by volume of consumption on UK MOD sites.</p><p>The MOD has reduced water consumption across its estate by 9% since 2010, thus exceeding a self-imposed target to achieve a 7% reduction in estate-wide water consumption and corresponding bills by 2015.</p><p>Work is continuing throughout the MOD estate to embed water use awareness, and achieve further reductions in water consumption. The Defence Infrastructure Organisation is implementing a Water Consumption Reduction programme, which will target 150 high demand sites to identify further water efficiency measures and improve the efficiency of water use.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165949/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T17:50:34.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165949/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165949/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165950","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-28","<p>The Ministry of Defence is responsible for a range of different storage facilities worldwide. This information is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165950/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:56:34.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165950/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165950/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-25","Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what storage facilities are owned by his Department; and what the estimated value of those facilities is.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","215982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165951","Cabinet Office","false","2014-12-02","<p>The Cabinet Office is committed to reducing the water consumption of its buildings. To date, my department has reduced its water consumption by 17.9% since 2009. Government is rationalising its estate, reducing the total number of properties, intensified occupation in remaining buildings and consequently reduced water usage and bills across the department.</p><p>Within the reduced estate, the Cabinet Office has introduced water reduction measures. These include motion-activated taps; removing unnecessary storage tanks and headers; and, installing additional metering and real time data to assist in monitoring of consumption to detect irregular usage patterns that could possibly be leakage.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165951/answer",,,,,"215954","2014-12-02T14:17:03.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165951/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165951/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Office; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165952","Department for Education","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Department for Education has made significant reductions to both its water usage and associated bills.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Total water use has been reduced by 43% since 2009-10, and the number of its offices falling within good and best practice office water benchmarks has been increased from 39% to 58% during the same period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These improvements have primarily been achieved by: installing efficiency devices such as tap aerators; flow control valves; and leak reduction work.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In taking this action, the Department has reduced its annual water bill by £107,000 since 2009-10, and continues to work towards identifying even greater efficiencies.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165952/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T17:39:37.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165952/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165952/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in her Department; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165953","Department for Education","false","2014-11-28","<p>Schools and local authorities are responsible for the recruitment of their supply teachers and deciding whether they use private agencies to recruit and employ them. If a supply teacher is employed by a private agency or their umbrella company, this is a private commercial arrangement between the school and agency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education does not provide guidance on tax and unemployment matters. These are matters for Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs and the Department for Work and Pensions, respectively.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165953/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T17:34:29.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165953/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165953/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Supply Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will provide guidance to supply teachers on the tax and unemployment implications of working for an umbrella company.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","215945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165954","Department for Education","false","2014-11-28","<p>The Department for Education funds sixth form colleges in England, not in the rest of the UK. We estimate that the total cost of VAT for sixth form colleges in England has been approximately £30 million for each of the last three years.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165954/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T11:57:18.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165954/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165954/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Sixth Form Colleges: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the amount of VAT paid by sixth form colleges in the UK in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","215913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165955","Department for Education","false","2014-11-28","<p>Officials at the Department for Education have had discussions with officials at HM Treasury regarding VAT paid by sixth form colleges. There are no plans to change existing policy.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165955/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T11:58:36.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165955/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165955/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Sixth Form Colleges: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on VAT paid by sixth form colleges.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","215930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165956","Department for Education","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Department for Education does not hold data on the schools in which Teach First participants are training or teaching. Teach First currently does not have partner schools in the Brighton and Hove area and has advised the Department that none of its former trainees are currently employed in a school in Brighton and Hove.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165956/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T15:31:42.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165956/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165956/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Teachers: Brighton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of teachers in Brighton and Hove who were trained as part of the Teach First programme; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165957","Department for Education","false","2014-12-01","<p>Since April 2010 schools in Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency have been directly allocated funding to support capital investment through the following programmes:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Priority Schools Building Programme</p></li><li><p>Free Schools</p></li><li><p>Building Schools for the Future</p></li><li><p>Academies Capital Maintenance Fund</p></li><li><p>Demographic Growth Capital Fund</p></li><li><p>Building Condition Improvement Fund</p></li><li><p>Locally Co-ordinated Voluntary Aided Programme</p></li><li><p>Devolved Formula Capital</p></li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition to the above, the Department for Education also allocates much of its available capital funding at a local authority level so that capital investment decisions can be made according to local priorities. These funds could be used by Blackpool and Lancashire local authorities to support capital investment in the Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency. These capital programmes include: Basic Need, Local Authority Capital Maintenance, and Universal Infant Free School Meals.</p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165957/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T15:37:03.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165957/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165957/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Blackpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which of her Department's capital investment programmes have involved expenditure in Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency since 2010.","false","Biography information for Paul Maynard","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","215794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165958","Department for Education","false","2014-12-01","<p>My Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, is committed to raising standards in maths education by learning from the leading systems in the world. However, she is yet to meet with her international counterparts specifically to discuss best practice for mathematics teaching.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education has adopted an evidence-based approach to our reform programme by studying what works in the highest performing and most improved education systems, such as Singapore and Shanghai. We have sought to implement the essence of those policies here.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At primary, our new national curriculum for maths has been inspired by these leading East Asian nations and focuses on building firm foundations and developing fluency so that pupils are able to recall and apply their knowledge as their understanding develops.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have launched a national network of 34 Maths Hubs, through which we are running the Mathematics Teacher Exchange Programme – England/China. This programme will develop a deep understanding of the Shanghai-style ‘mastery’ approach to maths teaching and trial its implementation within schools.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There is also clear evidence that points to the use of textbooks as a crucial element of the mastery approach. The 2011 Trends in International Mathematics and Science Study - an international comparison of maths and science teaching – found that in high-performing nations like Singapore, 70% of maths teachers use a textbook as a basis for instruction, whereas in England, only 10% do. That is why, from January 2015, all Maths Hubs will be participating in a project to assess whether a mastery approach to teaching supported by a high-quality textbook can be used to drive up the quality of primary maths teaching.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165958/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T17:33:06.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165958/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165958/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Mathematics: Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she had with her international counterparts on best practice for mathematics teaching; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165959","Department for Education","false","2014-11-28","<p>The Secretary of State has not made any assessment of information shared between schools and respective local authorities regarding children missing education. All schools (including academies, free schools and independent schools) have a legal duty to make returns to the relevant local authority and agree with that authority the regular interval at which such returns will be made. The school must inform the local authority of any pupil who fails to attend school regularly, or of any pupil who has been absent without the school’s permission for a continuous period of 10 days or more.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In cases where agreement is not reached as to the interval for such returns to be made to the local authority, the Secretary of State may determine the interval that the school then has to comply with.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165959/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T12:24:58.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165959/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165959/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Education: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the access provided to local authorities to registration information from academies, free schools and independent schools in order for them to discharge their obligation to monitor children who may be missing education.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","215856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165960","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-12-02","<p /> <p>This Government attaches a high priority to supporting couple relationships and committed a dedicated fund of £30 million for relationship support over the Spending Review period (2011-2015).</p><p> </p><p>We are funding a range of services through a number of expert providers to deliver relationship support provision, including preventative support targeted at couples at risk of family breakdown; activities to encourage the take-up of relationship support; and counselling for couples who may be experiencing difficulties.</p><p> </p><p>We have also introduced a Family Test which will mean that all new relevant domestic policies will need to be assessed for their impact on the family.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165960/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T11:49:44.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165960/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165960/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-11-25","Marriage Guidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent steps his Department has taken to support husbands and wives with relationship problems to enable families to stay together.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","215885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165961","Department for Education","false","2014-11-27","<p>The data requested is shown in the table below and is also published in Table LAE1 of the ‘Children looked after including adoption’ statistical first release [1].</p><p><strong>Number of looked after children adopted in Brighton and Hove local authority [1]</strong></p><p><strong>Years ending 31 March 2010 to 2014</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="5" rowspan="2"><p>Number of looked after children adopted during the year</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Brighton and Hove</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: SSDA903</p><p>Numbers have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption--2</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165961/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-27T17:39:52.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165961/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165961/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Adoption: Brighton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children were adopted in Brighton and Hove over the last five years for which figures are available; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165962","Department for Education","false","2014-11-28","<p>We have a duty to take swift action where we know children’s education is suffering. Schools in special measures will usually receive a monitoring inspection within 3 months and up to 4 further monitoring inspections over an 18-month period following the inspection that placed it in special measures. A school will normally be re-inspected within 24 months unless it is removed from special measures at a monitoring inspection.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for local authorities on intervening in ‘Schools Causing Concern’ is available online at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-causing-concern--2" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-causing-concern--2</a></p><p> </p><p>There are a range of powers that the local authority and the Secretary of State may use to drive school improvement. There is a clear expectation that a school in special measures will convert to an academy with a strong sponsor as this is the most reliable way of securing the radical improvement the school requires. The Department writes to these schools to begin this process within five days of being notified by Ofsted of the judgement.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165962/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T11:40:56.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165962/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165962/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-11-25","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what timeframe her Department has set for schools in special measures to improve their performance before it takes action.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","215892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165963","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Department does not hold a breakdown of domestic Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) participants by council tax band.</p><p>The Department does provide detailed information on domestic RHI accreditations as part of our monthly release of RHI statistics. These data are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/renewable-heat-incentive-renewable-heat-premium-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/renewable-heat-incentive-renewable-heat-premium-payment-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165963/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:20:13.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165963/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165963/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households in each council tax band are in receipt of payments under the renewable heat incentive.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","215889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165964","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Department does not hold a breakdown of Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) accreditations by Parliamentary constituency.</p><p>The Department does report the number of domestic RHI accreditations (i.e. installations which have been accepted onto the scheme and are eligible to receive RHI payments) by local authority as part of our monthly release of Renewable Heat Incentive statistics. These data are available in Table 2.10 at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rhi-and-rhpp-deployment-data-october-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rhi-and-rhpp-deployment-data-october-2014</a>.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165964/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:19:53.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165964/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165964/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many households in each (a) parliamentary constituency and (b) local authority are in receipt of payments under the renewable heat incentive.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","215890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165965","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-28","<p>The Department does not hold this information. However, we recently published an Energy Investment Report which showed significant levels of investment since 2010.</p><p>· January 2010 and 2013 mobilised over £45 billion in low carbon energy infrastructure,1 which will also support up to 250,000 jobs in the low-carbon energy generation sector by 2020.</p><p>· In 2013 DECC estimates that over £14bn was invested in electricity generation and networks.</p><p>· Nearly £8 billion invested across a range of renewable technologies in 2013 alone – a record year.2</p><p>· UK is the most attractive market in the world for investment in offshore wind and marine renewables.</p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em> <em>DECC estimates based on EMR Delivery Plan modelling</em></p><p><strong><em>[2]</em></strong> <em>Bloomberg New Energy Finance, nominal, converted to pounds sterling.</em></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165965/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:36:53.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165965/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165965/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Energy: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much energy investment of each type was made by energy companies in each year since 1984.","false","Biography information for Mr Michael Meacher","Oldham West and Royton","Mr Michael Meacher","215898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165966","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Buildings Performance Institute Europe’s report – ‘Renovation Strategies of Selected EU Countries’ – assesses the Building Renovation Strategies submitted by ten EU Member States to the European Commission in accordance with Article 4 of the EU Energy Efficiency Directive (2012/27/EU).</p><p>Of the ten Member States assessed, the UK’s Building Renovation Strategy is considered, along with the reports of three other Member States, to be the most comprehensive and compliant with the provisions of Article 4.</p><p>The Department will reflect on the report’s suggestions and give consideration to how these can be addressed in future iterations of the UK Building Renovation Strategy; the Energy Efficiency Directive requires Member States to update their strategies by no later than 30 April 2017.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165966/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:20:35.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165966/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165966/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Energy: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the findings on the UK in the report of the Building Performance Institute Europe on Renovation strategies of selected EU countries, published in November 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","215902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165967","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>The Department reports the number of 'live' Green Deal Plans (with measures installed) by Region, up to 30th June 2014 in Table 1.7 of the quarterly official statistics publication.</p><p>As at the end of June 2014 there were 1,587 'live' Green Deal Plans in Great Britain. These are not evenly distributed across all local authorities, and it remains possible that a household may be identifiable if they were the only household to have a Green Deal finance Plan in their Local Authority area. This would not be consistent with the fair processing notice that they were given when they entered the plan.</p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165967/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:24:06.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165967/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165967/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 24 November 2014 to Question 214561, on the green deal scheme, what confidentiality reasons prevent that data being broken down to a lower geographical area.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","215906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165968","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>Ofgem will publish its next annual Social Obligations Report, providing information on suppliers’ performance in 2013, before the end of this year’s parliamentary session.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165968/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:23:41.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165968/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165968/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 24 November 2014 to Question 214693, when the next Domestic Supplies Obligations annual report will be published.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","215907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165969","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-10","<p>The Energy Company Obligation (ECO) uses a range of proxies to find low income and vulnerable households at risk of fuel poverty. These proxies are used to define eligibility for the Affordable Warmth and Carbon Savings Community Obligation elements of ECO.</p><p>The original ECO Order, which defines the eligibility criteria, is available here:</p><p><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2012/3018/schedule/1/made" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2012/3018/schedule/1/made</a></p><p>Please note, new legislation is in the process of finalisation following Parliamentary debates in November 2014.</p><p>The eligibility criteria, which help identify low income households, work in tandem with the ECO scoring system. This encourages delivery in households with the highest energy costs. Taken together, this means ECO is effective in reaching fuel poor households.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165969/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-10T16:25:22.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165969/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165969/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 21 November 2014 to Question 214565, which proxies are used to find low income and vulnerable households at risk of fuel poverty under the Energy Company Obligation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","215908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165970","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>A timetable for future statistical releases for the Department can be found here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statistical-releases-timetable-for-twelve-months-ahead" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/statistical-releases-timetable-for-twelve-months-ahead</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165970/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T15:22:15.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165970/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165970/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 24 November 2014 to Question 214562, on the Energy Companies Obligation, when the next quarterly official statistics will be published.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","215909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165971","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-03","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) already utilises water efficient appliances, including waterless urinals. In addition, over the past twelve months DECC has undertaken a number of measures aimed at reducing its water use and water bills. These include undertaking an independent water audit, increased maintenance on its hot and cold water dispensers to make them more efficient, the closing and draining down of its cooling towers over the winter months when chilling is not required, staff awareness raising measures and maintenance work to fix a small number of leaking taps.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165971/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-03T16:01:44.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165971/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165971/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165972","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>A comprehensive review of the feed-in tariff scheme (FITs) in 2012 introduced degression mechanisms for all technologies to prevent overcompensation and deliver value-for-money for energy bill payers. Following consultation, degression bands at the sub-100kW capacities were combined in an effort to support the deployment of small-scale turbines. A re-assessment of the FITs degression bands and tariff rates, as well as their effect on deployment, will form part of the next review of FITs in 2015.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165972/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T15:41:35.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165972/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165972/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Wind Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment he has made of the effect on small-scale wind turbine development of the removal of 15kw Fee-in-Tariff bracket in December 2012.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","215973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165973","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-12-01","<p>The 2014 United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) Emissions Gap report makes clear that while existing levels of global mitigation ambition are not enough to put us on a cost-effective 2˚C trajectory, there is still more than enough global emissions reduction potential to achieve 2030 emissions levels that would be consistent with 2˚C. However, realising this potential will require political will across all countries, and a significant increase in global mitigation action before 2030.</p><p>The Report effectively supports the Government's climate change strategy, of taking strong action at home within the legal framework of the Climate Change Act 2008, pressing for ambition from the EU, which recently agreed to a 2030 domestic GHG emissions reduction target of at least 40%, and pushing for credible action from other countries in the context of agreeing a global legally binding agreement at the UNFCCC Conference of the Parties in Paris in December 2015.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165973/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T16:24:32.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165973/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165973/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-11-25","Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment he has made of the implications for the Government's climate change strategy of the United Nations Environment Programme report, The Emissions Gap Report 2014, published in November 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","215929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165974","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-28","<p>Agricultural land and soils form an integral part of the natural environment. While the Government recognises that solar power can have a role to play in reducing carbon emissions, the loss of agricultural land to solar arrays constitutes damage to that element of the environment. The Government therefore discourages the construction of solar farms on the best and most versatile agricultural land and has withdrawn farm subsidies from land occupied by solar farms. The Government believes that farm subsidies should be targeted at land used for growing food and crops.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165974/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T14:48:36.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165974/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165974/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-25","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to balance the environmental damage caused to agricultural land by solar farm developments with the need to mitigate the effects of climate change when considering whether farm subsidies should be paid on farm land occupied by solar farms.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","215967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165975","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-12-02","<p>Core Defra has reduced water consumption and costs through investment in water saving measures such as flow restrictors, rainwater harvesting, low flush toilet cisterns and waterless urinals. Smart metering also enables Core Defra to monitor and target excessive consumption, identify leaks and ensure building systems are operating to optimum efficiency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Rationalisation of the estate has also delivered significant savings. For example, since April 2012 core Defra has reduced its London estate from four to two properties, making more efficient use of space and reducing water consumption as part of the overall strategy.</p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165975/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T17:11:22.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165975/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165975/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in her Department; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165976","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-28","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) as the UK’s competition authority can carry out investigations where there is evidence of abuse of a dominant position or market abuse. Whilst the Government does not generally intervene in what businesses charge consumers for their goods and services we do recognise the concerns over the current pressures on milk prices. That is why my hon Friend the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs brought forward and chaired a meeting of the Dairy Supply Chain Forum last week.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Members, which include retailer representatives, discussed the recommendations made in the recent independent review of the dairy industry voluntary Code of Practice, one of which was to explore the possibility of expanding adoption of the Code within the supply chain to include retailers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165976/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T14:29:09.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165976/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165976/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-25","Milk: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will hold discussions with the major supermarkets on measures to reduce the practice of suppressing retail milk price as a loss leader.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","215894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165977","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-12-01","<p>Since 2010, approximately £96.2 million of Flood and Coastal Erosion Risk Management Grant in aid funding has been spent in the Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency, with a further £23.6 million currently committed to be spent by October 2015.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165977/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-01T13:39:23.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165977/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165977/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-25","Blackpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which of her Department's capital investment programmes have involved expenditure in Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency since 2010.","false","Biography information for Paul Maynard","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","215795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165978","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-12-02","<p>We have made no direct representations to the Government of Russia on this issue. The UK strongly supports comments made by NATO Secretary General Stoltenberg last week calling on Russia to obey the norms of international air traffic and understand that he has plans to follow up with Russia directly on this point. NATO Foreign Ministers, including the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), will discuss Russia’s actions at the forthcoming meeting on 2 December. The UK strongly supports exploring options to improve military transparency between NATO and Russia.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165978/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T15:38:19.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165978/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165978/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Russian Federation on that country's increased patrols near NATO airspace; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165979","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-28","<p>I have not previously met Sheikh Nasser bin Hamad Al Khalifa of Bahrain and I do not currently have any meetings with him planned.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165979/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:57:56.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165979/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165979/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Bahrain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, on how many occasions he has met Prince Nasser bin Hamad of Bahrain in an official capacity; and when the next such meeting is planned.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","215826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165980","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-12-02","<p>In the last two years, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office has implemented, or is implementing, the following measures to reduce water consumption in its UK estate:</p><p>•Reducing water flow pressure</p><p>•Adjusting urinal flushing</p><p>•Installation of shower and tap regulators</p><p>•Installation of single flush toilets and low flush urinals</p><p>•Water softening on data-centre chilled water system</p><p>•Installation of more efficient washing machines</p><p>•Installation of toilet cistern water saving devices</p><p>•Extensive installation of water sub-meters</p><p>•Analysis of water consumption per building to identify waste</p><p>•Grey water harvesting at our Hanslope Park data-centre building</p><p>•Water audit at Hanslope Park</p><p>•Leak detection</p><p>By the quarter July to September 2014, these measures had reduced water consumption by 27.5% compared to the same period in 2013. That represents an annual water saving of 18,256m3.</p><p>There have been no specific actions yet to renegotiate water tariffs.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165980/answer",,,,,,"2014-12-02T15:40:39.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165980/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165980/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to reduce water (a) usage and (b) bills in his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","215962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165981","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-28","<p>Freedom of expression in Iran is severely restricted. Iran has more journalists in prison than almost any other country. New outlets and online media are heavily censored and the majority of newspapers are now government controlled. We continue to urge Iran to guarantee the rights of all its citizens in line with its international obligations. We most recently raised our concerns around freedom of expression during Iran’s Universal Periodic Review during the UN Human Rights Council on 31 October.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165981/answer",,,,,"215938","2014-11-28T13:42:01.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165981/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165981/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the level of press freedom in Iran.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","215935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165982","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-28","Iran systematically filters and restricts access to the internet. Millions of websites are blocked, including social media sites such as Twitter and Facebook. Many Iranian citizens find technical ways around the restrictions but their online activity can put them at risk. In May 2014, eight Iranians were sentenced to a combined 123 years in prison for their Facebook activities. Charges included blasphemy, insulting the Supreme Leader, and spreading propaganda against the system. We urge Iran to allow freedom of expression, and respect the rights of all its citizens in line with its international obligations. We most recently raised our concerns around freedom of expression during Iran’s Universal Periodic Review at the UN Human Rights Council on 31 October.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165982/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:43:52.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165982/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165982/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the extent of restriction of access to the internet in Iran.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","215936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165983","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-28","In 2013, President Rouhani made a number of comments in support of greater religious freedom in Iran. Unfortunately, there has been no change in Iran’s approach over the past year. Religious minority groups in Iran continue to face widespread discrimination. The UK has repeatedly called on the Iranian government to end all persecution of individuals on the basis of their faith, and to guarantee the human rights of all Iranians.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165983/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T13:54:13.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165983/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165983/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the level of religious freedom in Iran.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","215937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165984","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-28","<p>Freedom of expression in Iran is severely restricted. Iran has more journalists in prison than almost any other country. New outlets and online media are heavily censored and the majority of newspapers are now government controlled. We continue to urge Iran to guarantee the rights of all its citizens in line with its international obligations. We most recently raised our concerns around freedom of expression during Iran’s Universal Periodic Review during the UN Human Rights Council on 31 October.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165984/answer",,,,,"215935","2014-11-28T13:42:01.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165984/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165984/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-25","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Iranian counterpart on the detention of journalists in Iran.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","215938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165985","Department of Health","false","2014-11-28","<p><em>Improving Outcomes: A Strategy for Cancer</em>, published in January 2011, committed over £450 million over the four years up to 2014-15 to achieve earlier diagnosis of symptomatic cancer. The earlier diagnosis money is designed to support centrally led Be Clear on Cancer (BCOC) campaigns; improved direct general practitioner (GP) access to four key diagnostic tests to support the diagnosis of brain tumours, bowel, lung, and ovarian cancers; and increased testing and treatment costs in secondary care. GPs are able to access these tests directly in cases where the two-week urgent referral pathway is not appropriate but a patient’s symptoms require further investigation. The intention is that more people presenting with relevant symptoms, including patients aged over 75 will be tested and at an earlier stage. NHS England monitors the use of these diagnostic tests through the Diagnostic Imaging Dataset.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2011 the Department and Public Health England (since 2013) in partnership with NHS England (including NHS Improving Quality) and other stakeholders have run national BCOC campaigns for bladder and kidney, bowel, breast and lung cancers; regional campaigns for ovarian, oesophagogastric cancers, and local pilot campaigns to raise awareness of four symptoms of unexplained bleeding, lump, pain, and weight loss; and awareness of skin and prostate cancers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>BCOC campaigns are aimed at men and women over the age of 55 and their key influencers (e.g. family members) and use television (at regional and national level), radio and press and face-to-face events. The breast cancer campaign from February to March 2014 was specifically aimed at women over 70 as there is considerable evidence that many older women are not aware that they are still at risk.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2012, to increase the awareness of cancer amongst GPs and support GPs to assess all patients more effectively, the Department funded the British Medical Journal (BMJ) Learning to provide an e-learning tool for GPs. The modules include tackling late diagnosis; risk assessment tools; and cancer pathway and the role of primary care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2013, Macmillan Cancer Support, partly funded by the Department, piloted an electronic cancer decision support tool for GPs to use in their routine practice. Following the pilot, Macmillan is now offering the tool free of charge to all GPs in the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is in the process of updating the Referral Guidelines for Suspected Cancer (2005) to ensure that it reflects latest evidence and can continue to support GPs to identify patients with the symptoms of suspected cancer and urgently refer them as appropriate. NICE’s draft is currently out for consultation until 9 January 2015. The anticipated publication date for the revised guidelines is May 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Men and women aged 75 and over are able to self-refer for bowel screening every two years if they wish. Women over 70 are able to self-refer every three years for breast screening.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Finally, NHS England in their recent publication ‘Five Year Forward View’ (October 2014) acknowledge that cancer survival is below the European average, especially for people aged over 75. The report highlights that improvements in outcomes will require action on better prevention; swifter access to diagnosis, and better treatment and care for all those diagnosed with cancer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165985/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-28T12:20:57.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165985/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165985/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-25","Cancer: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps (a) his Department and (b) NHS England are taking to improve early diagnosis of cancer for patients aged over 75.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","215939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165986","Department of Health","false","2014-12-02","<p>National Health Service funding has risen in each year of this parliament and is £12.7 billion higher in cash terms in 2014-15 than in 2010-11. Health funding will again grow in real terms in 2015-16, which means an additional £2.1 billion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has responsibility for clinical commissioning group (CCG) allocations and, as a result of Government protecting the overall health budget for NHS England, NHS England has in turn ensured that all CCGs are receiving a funding increase at least matching inflation, as predicted at the time of the announcement, in 2014-15 and 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The funding that CCGs receive is not ring fenced and as such it is up to CCGs at a local level to decide how to allocate their funding in regards to awareness and prevention.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Mandate to NHS England requires it to ensure that the new commissioning system promotes and supports participation by NHS organisations and NHS patients in research funded by both commercial and non-commercial organisations. This includes ensuring payment of treatment costs for NHS patients taking part in research funded by Government and Research Charity partner organisations. The main Government funders of health research are the National Institute for Health Research and the Medical Research Council.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165986/answer",,,,,"215919 ; 215920 ; 215922","2014-12-02T17:35:29.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165986/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165986/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-25","Prostate Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of clinical commissioning group budgets is allocated to prostate cancer research, awareness and prevention in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","215921"
